The error is not deterministic. The machines do not have termination protection. Some machines can be terminated without a problem and the next round you get problems.

issues.title: OpenJDK 9 broken?
issues.body: the function that is called is installOracleJDK

issues.title: OpenJDK 8 install broken
issues.body: The configuration file for openjdk 8 doesn't look the same as for the other openjdk's. So perhaps it has not been converted.

issues.title: warmup and ramp down period hdr not modified
issues.body: With the recent change in 0.11 with cutting of data for warmup/ramp down, the hdr files are not modified. So the hdr files contains all data including the warmup/ramp-down period.

issues.title: Boot: SSL config not picked up
issues.body: The network config is completely replaced by the template content

commitsDetails.commitMessage:
Fixes boot networking issues

The problem was that the whole network configuration was completely
overridden. And if e.g. ssl was configured it is lost.

fix #1611

issues.title: Boot: project should automatically run in 'workdir'
issues.body: Currently all artifacts are stored in the root of the project; making it messy

issues.title: Boot: premature abort of test doesn't work
issues.body: Control c doesn't work

commitsDetails.commitMessage: Fixes boot problem: java not available on path when starting agent. Fix #1595

issues.title: upload directory downloaded
issues.body:
The upload directory is copied into the workers directory, and downloaded when the test completes. If the upload directory contains large files, these will be downloaded potentially multiple times per machine. 

So the upload directory should be excluded from downloading.

issues.body: Normally session id is generated, but when using same session id and doing multiple runs, then startup failures. Probably because directories/files already exist

issues.title: AbstractAsyncStreamer doesn't stop in case of error
issues.body:
The AbstractAsyncStreamer doesn't stop in case of error because the callback doesn't signal there is a problem. So you get huge quantities of useless log and worker has problems dying.

The deeper problem is that the callback get rejected for execution; and therefor the callback logic doesn't get called. But why does the RejectedExecutionException not get noticed?

issues.title: Bug in harakiri
issues.body:
The problem is in the startup of the harakiri monitor after a test completes. Instead of setting the actual key/value, the literal values are taken. So if you have your identity configured as '''bla/ec2.identity''', then '''bla/ec2.identity''' is the literal value.

The cause of this is the SimulatorProperties.asMap function which returns the values without replacements being applied.

issues.title: Coordinator-Remote not exiting
issues.body:
This is an intermittent issue wherein  control not coming back to calling process after calling coordinator-remote for various tasks like (worker-kill, worker-start etc)

Ex: coordinator-remote worker-start --count 2

commitsDetails.commitMessage:
Fixes problem with coordinator-remote not completing

The problem is that the call id can't be negative, but in 50%
of the times it was. If the call id is negative, then there is
no registered future and therefor a response doesn't trigger
the future to complete.

Fixes #1268

commitsDetails.commitMessage:
Lot more work on testing

Agent cli has been cleaned up a bit

Remote available wieh running in regular mode fix #1239
Control c should work for monolithic mode fix #1238

issues.title: Coordinator 0 duration by default
issues.body: Currently there is a default duration of 1 minute, needs to change to 0 indicating that the test will decide how long to run

issues.title: Timestep: async testing and intended starttime.
issues.body:
For asynchronous tests, the expected start-time isn't available. So asynchronous tests can only make use of actual start-time, reintroducing the coordinated omission problem.

So it should be possible to expose the intended start-time as argument.

commitsDetails.commitMessage:
Fixes async testing

The problem with async testing is that the timestep method doesn't know the completion,
and therefor can't record the latency. To solve this problem, the timestep method gets
the starttime injected as argument and it is up to the completion handler to record
the right value in the probe.

Fix #1235

issues.title: Coordinator download not downloading the member files and throwing content in root

commitsDetails.commitMessage: Fixes various issues with downloading fix #1234

issues.title: Download not running after failure of regular coordinator
PerformanceTracker keeps old data
issues.body:
The PerformanceCollector accumulates data from previous runs.

When doing multilpe coordinator-remote run commands, the performance has the data from the previous run added on top of the existing run.

issues.title: Test explicit addressing only
issues.body:
Currently we have a complex schema for test addressing, perhaps better if it is made explicit. The advantage of explicit test addressing is that we can control which member is going to run which test. Currently all non global phases are executed on all members in the cluster, but actually it only needs to be executed on the drivers. 

So when the test start to run, it determines its set of drivers and all global or non global calls, it will execute on that set of drivers. All other workers it will not talk to.

issues.title: TestId problematic when parallel testsuites
issues.body:
The testId is being used do identify a test; e.g. when there is a test failure, the test id is used to look up the TestCase. This is a problem when you want to do 2 simple remote parallel testsuites because you need to explicitly change their test id.

The TestAddress is unique; so that should be used as correlation id. Then the testid is just something nice for the screen but has not deeper meaning.

issues.title: Benchmark report: latency not rendering problem
issues.body:
Hmm.. when the the output directory doesn't exist, the remaining latencies are not plotted.

When the output directory exists (e.g. from previous run), then the remaining latencies are plotted.

So it must be related to some kind of simple file issue

commitsDetails.commitMessage:
Fix #1112

The problem is that the html image was put before the rendering of the image
and if the image doesn't exist, then the html code for the image is not inserted.

So rendering should be done before the html image insertion.

issues.title: Benchmark report: when single benchmark; multiple latency plots
issues.body: Something fishy is happening with the latency plotting.

issues.title: Security risk: HarakiriMonitor ec2 credentials
issues.body: The HarakiriMonitor gets the ec2 credentials as command line settings; meaning that they will be visible in ps aux + they will be logged into the bash logging. Probably better to replace it by environment variables so the credentials are less visible

The message should be more informative.

issues.title: Faster shutdown on test failure
issues.body:
If a test throws a critical failure, the system should shutdown a lot faster. It is still trying to complete the phases. There should be some kind of time window; when this window has expired, the coordinator starts to send requests to the member it should just kill itself no matter which tests are running.

One of the problems is that in case of test failure, and the workers not shutting down, jfr files are not being written to disk. So we don't see what happened during the failure

issues.title: If class has trailing space
issues.body: If the class definition in the test has a trailing space, there is an error that the testId is not a valid filename. Some trimming needs to be applied here.

issues.title: Race in PerformanceStateContainer
issues.body: Because queue's are swapped, it can happen that a performancestate is added to a queue that moments later gets swapped out and processed. So you get an unprocessed PerformanceState on the queue which will never been seen

commitsDetails.commitMessage:
Fixes #854

It has been solved by removing the replacement of the queue. So the queue is only drained; never deleted. Therefor you
won't loose any items due to swapping out a queue.

Merge pull request #855 from pveentjer/fix/854-race-performancestatecontainer

Fixes #854

issues.title: Unable to execute coordinator and worker on same machine under the same user
issues.body: When setting up a simulator test with cloud provider `static`, I add the coordinator machine's IP address in `agents.txt` and configure in `simulator.properties` the current user to also execute the worker processes. In this configuration case, during startup the coordinator process is killed.

issues.title: Continuous Monitor should aggregate received samples
issues.body:
as discussed with @Donnerbart:

Continous Monitor uses 2 intervals:
1. measuring interval - controls size of measurement window on workers
2. displaying interval - how often we display data on Coordinator

Measuring interval tends to be smaller the displaying interval. 

Let's assume measuring interval is 10s and displaying interval is 30s. -> We receive about 3 samples during the a single displaying interval. 

Right now the Continuous Monitor will display only the very last sample. Data from other samples are ignored by the Continuous Monitor -> the maximum latency, percentiles. etc. are misleading.

The main performance.log file that is kept on the coordinator is broken. The value that are stored here don't reflect the 'total performance' log messages when the completes. 

This is an example of such a 'total message':

```
INFO  23:46:07 Total performance        100.00%     214,383,958 ops      714,613.19 ops/s
INFO  23:46:07   Agent 10.212.1.114      24.94%      53,459,635 ops      178,198.78 ops/s

```

And the corresponding log entry:
738661.1100404703

Sometimes the values are like 10/20% different.The problem is that now it has become a lot more difficult to run many tests after each other and see if there is a performance variation.

To resolve this issue we first need to determine the true performance and then see who is right.

```
logFrequency = 1000000
performanceUpdateFrequency = 1000
keyLocality = random

```

The test doesn't execute operations due to an exception in the logging:

```
com.hazelcast.simulator.utils.BindException: Property [com.hazelcast.simulator.tests.synthetic.SyntheticTest$Worker.logFrequency] does not exist
        at com.hazelcast.simulator.utils.PropertyBindingSupport.bindProperty(PropertyBindingSupport.java:106)
        at com.hazelcast.simulator.utils.PropertyBindingSupport.bindProperty(PropertyBindingSupport.java:90)
        at com.hazelcast.simulator.utils.PropertyBindingSupport.bindOptionalProperty(PropertyBindingSupport.java:83)
        at com.hazelcast.simulator.worker.TestContainer.spawnWorkerThreads(TestContainer.java:406)
        at com.hazelcast.simulator.worker.TestContainer.invokeRunWithWorkerMethod(TestContainer.java:387)
        at com.hazelcast.simulator.worker.TestContainer.run(TestContainer.java:217)
        at com.hazelcast.simulator.worker.TestContainer.invoke(TestContainer.java:192)
        at com.hazelcast.simulator.worker.WorkerCommandRequestProcessor$WorkerCommandRequestProcessorThread$1.doRun(WorkerCommandRequestProcessor.java:217)
        at com.hazelcast.simulator.worker.WorkerCommandRequestProcessor$CommandThread.run(WorkerCommandRequestProcessor.java:368)
```

So there are 2 problems here:
- the test doesn't stop when there is a binding problem
- the test is trying to bind on the worker and not on the test

Please get this fixed + tested.

issues.title: MapStreamer requires Hazelcast 3.5 or newer to work properly
issues.body:
The new `MapStreamer` requires Hazelcast 3.5 or newer to work properly. In older version there are bugs with the used asynchronous methods which create a failure during runtime.

Our idea is to create a Factory which checks the Hazelcast version and returns a sync or async implementation of the `MapStreamer`.

issues.title: NPE in Provisioner when Simulator was compiled without git metadata
issues.body:
When you e.g. download the Simulator sources as ZIP archive from GitHub there is no git repository/metadata available.

If you compile Simulator and use it, the `Provisioner` fails with a NPE, because it tries to print the git revision of Simulator, which is not available in that case.

The issue will be the underlaying `GitInfo` which should not fail in that case.

issues.title: Make Simulator run on localhost
issues.body:
At the moment you cannot use `127.0.0.1` as ip address for an agent. This causes trouble when you are not connected to a network and want to run Simulator (plane, airport, bad hotel wifi). Could be an issue for our solution architects in the field.

There is already a `--bindaddress` option in the agent which I use for the smoke test (which would fail otherwise). Maybe we should use this per default and get rid of the automatic hostname resolution via the google.com ping. This will also fail if a local test cluster is not connected to the internet.

issues.title: Probe binding should honour the fail-fast principle
issues.body:
Currently unknown probe- properties are silently ignored. 
This leads to waste of time when there is a typo or wrong property format used. We should fail fast on unknown probe configuration.

issues.title: OperationSelector should not cause synchronization overhead
issues.body:
OperationSelectors currently cause synchronization overhead because the same selector is used between all workers. This is a bad thing; we don't want to add overhead in the testing framework itself.

To solve this issue the OperationSelector should be added in the AbstractWorker; where each AbstractWorker gets its own instance.

This task is fixed when there is no synchronization anymore.

issues.title: jars not copied anymore
issues.body:
After merging the git support, the Hazelcast jars are not being updated on the remote system any more. I have verified this by adding extra logging in Hazelcast jar and the logging never appeared. I'm using:

HAZELCAST_VERSION_SPEC=maven=3.5-SNAPSHOT

As soon as I reverted stabilizer to the version just before the git support merge, everything works exactly like it should and I see my logging.

So it must be a change that was added by the git support or any other change following it.

issues.title: assertTrueEventually needs to take execution time in consideraton
issues.body: Currently the assertTrueEventually doesn't take the execution time of the assertTask in consideration. So if the task takes a lot of time; the assertTrueEventually takes a lot more time than expected.

issues.title: Cluster startup problem not logged
issues.body:
When a cluster fails to startup, the exception isn't logged. THis is very freaky since the exception is detected by the failure monitor, meaning that the .exception file was written. And this is only possible if the ExceptionReporter was used; and this class  always logs the exception.

Perhaps that log4j has not flushed its log buffers.

issues.title: Clients can't connect to hz cluster
issues.body:
Don't know if this is something in HZ, stabilizer or ec2.

Members can connect to each other fine.

Clients can't connect to members at all. Tried putting a minute delay between server startup completion and client startup, no fix.

issues.title: Stabilizer Tests crashing with  UnsupportedOperationException HazelcastClient.getLoggingService
issues.body:
Hi @pveentjer , @jerrinot 
Test that were working ok, are now failing with

java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException
    at com.hazelcast.client.HazelcastClient.getLoggingService(HazelcastClient.java:442)

did we add a new feature to stabilizer ?

issues.body:

One test failed and I got this output. How can operation count be negative.

commitsDetails.commitMessage:

issues.title: mama monkey: exceptions are not being picked up
issues.body: A new member created by mama monkey can throw an exception e.g. because there is no test active. But these exceptions are not picked up by the worker manager.

issues.title: Test should be started not before the cluster is stable
issues.body: I suspect the test is now started even before a cluster is formed properly. This can jeopardize test results.

issues.body:

maybe the .hprof at 1.7 GB is to big back on the "ec2-user" box or my account on the "ec2-user" box.

issues.title: archetype: package name generated is no good
Identity from file is not working
GCE: Can't startup RHEL image
issues.body: The image is not found, even though it is available in the UI.

issues.title: Any value in PUBLIC_KEY is accepted
issues.body:
I was having troubles with the cloud (the instance spawned was refusing to let me in) and I suspected that provisioner can't see the public key file in the current directory.
So I decided to check if a missing file would be reported in any way and changed value to

 PUBLIC_KEY=xxxkey.pub

And despite the fact I do not have file with such a name, provisioner --scale 1 did not complain about it and proceed with deployment (still failing to SSH to the host).

I think some validation should be performed before going on...

issues.title: GCE: Firewall quota exceeded.
issues.body: Firewall rules are not reused and not cleaned after termination, so eventually you get too many firewall rules and can't start up new machines.

issues.title: GCE: bootdisk is not destroyed on termination
When worker fails, no logging
issues.body: When a worker fails to be started, e.g. bad JVM settings, then there is no logging explaining what happened.

issues.title: No error when agent fails to be started
ec2 login issue
issues.body: There is an ec2 login issue if the user of the instance is the same as the user of the spawning instance. E.g. ec2-user.

issues.title: improved heart attack handeling
issues.body:
- when a heart attack of one of the trainees is encountered..  something should be done.
  - Currently the test aborts.
  - Start the next workout.

Currently the functionality is a bit unpredictable. Needs to be improved
